# Task Format

Every task file in `tasks/` follows one structure so agents and reviewers can
scan them quickly and tooling can validate them
(`{{CHECKS_DIR}}/check_tasks.py`).

## Required structure

````markdown
# {{TASK_ID_EXAMPLE}} — Short imperative title

## Goal
- What outcome this task delivers.

## Non-goals
- What this task explicitly does not do.

## Context
- Why now; links to related code, tasks, or docs.

## Required changes
- [ ] Concrete, reviewable change.

## Tests
- [ ] Test or verification requirement.

## Docs
- [ ] Documentation update (or "none — reason").

## Acceptance criteria
- [ ] Observable condition that means "done".

## Verification
```bash
{{TEST_CMD}}
```

## Forbidden changes
- Mixing mechanical moves with semantic refactors.
- Introducing unrelated feature work.
````

## Field guidance

- The H1 is `# <ID> — <title>`. The id matches the pattern in `agentkit.toml`
  (`[tasks].id_regex`) and uses a registered prefix (see [tasks/README](/tasks/README.md)).
- **Goal / Non-goals / Context / Forbidden changes** are plain bullets.
- **Required changes / Tests / Docs / Acceptance criteria** use checkbox todos
  (`- [ ]` open, `- [x]` done) so progress is mechanically visible.
- Keep tasks small. If a task needs more than a handful of required changes,
  split it into slices that each ship independently.
- A file in `tasks/done/` carries a completion date (`YYYY-MM-DD`) and a
  reference to the PR or commit that closed it, and has no open `- [ ]` todos.

## Optional `## Maturity`

Add a `## Maturity` section when the stop-state is ambiguous (a slice that lands
partial-but-correct rather than fully complete). See
[task-maturity](/{{DOCS_AGENT_DIR}}/task-maturity.md) for the closure rule.
